#Text=Seven long years and more ( Greek)-ing it , at Greek and Latin ;
#Text=Four years at his probations and his negations -- the fine statue still lying in the middle of the marble block , -- and nothing done , but his tools sharpened to hew it out !
#Text=-- 'Tis a piteous delay ! --
#Text=Was not the great Julius Scaliger within an ace of never getting his tools sharpened at all ?

#Text=-- Forty-four years old was he before he could manage his Greek ; -- and Peter Damianus , lord bishop of Ostia , as all the world knows , could not so much as read , when he was of man 's estate . --

#Text=And Baldus himself , as eminent as he turned out after , entered upon the law so late in life , that every body imagined he intended to be an advocate in the other world : no wonder , when Eudamidas , the son of Archidamas , heard Xenocrates at seventy-five disputing about wisdom , that he asked gravely , -- If the old man be yet disputing and enquiring concerning wisdom , -- what time will he have to make use of it ?

#Text=Yorick listened to my father with great attention ; there was a seasoning of wisdom unaccountably mixed up with his strangest whims , and he had sometimes such illuminations in the darkest of his eclipses , as almost atoned for them : -- be wary , Sir , when you imitate him .

#Text=I am convinced , Yorick , continued my father , half reading and half discoursing , that there is a North-west passage to the intellectual world ; and that the soul of man has shorter ways of going to work , in furnishing itself with knowledge and instruction , than we generally take with it .
#Text=-- But , alack !
#Text=all fields have not a river or a spring running besides them ; -- every child , Yorick , has not a parent to point it out .
#Text=-- The whole entirely depends , added my father , in a low voice , upon the auxiliary verbs , Mr. Yorick .
#Text=Had Yorick trod upon Virgil 's snake , he could not have looked more surprised .

#Text=-- I am surprised too , cried my father , observing it , -- and I reckon it as one of the greatest calamities which ever befel the republic of letters , That those who have been entrusted with the education of our children , and whose business it was to open their minds , and stock them early with ideas , in order to set the imagination loose upon them , have made so little use of the auxiliary verbs in doing it , as they have done -- So that , except Raymond Lullius , and the elder Pelegrini , the last of which arrived to such perfection in the use of ' em , with his topics , that , in a few lessons , he could teach a young gentleman to discourse with plausibility upon any subject , pro and con , and to say and write all that could be spoken or written concerning it , without blotting a word , to the admiration of all who beheld him .
#Text=-- I should be glad , said Yorick , interrupting my father , to be made to comprehend this matter .
#Text=You shall , said my father .

#Text=The highest stretch of improvement a single word is capable of , is a high metaphor , -- for which , in my opinion , the idea is generally the worse , and not the better ; -- but be that as it may , -- when the mind has done that with it -- there is an end , -- the mind and the idea are at rest , -- until a second idea enters ; -- and so on .

#Text=Now the use of the Auxiliaries is , at once to set the soul a-going by herself upon the materials as they are brought her ; and by the versability of this great engine , round which they are twisted , to open new tracts of enquiry , and make every idea engender millions .
#Text=You excite my curiosity greatly , said Yorick .
#Text=For my own part , quoth my uncle Toby , I have given it up . --
#Text=The Danes , an ' please your honour , quoth the corporal , who were on the left at the siege of Limerick , were all auxiliaries .
#Text=-- And very good ones , said my uncle Toby .
#Text=-- But the auxiliaries , Trim , my brother is talking about , -- I conceive to be different things .
#Text=--
#Text=-- You do ? said my father , rising up .
#Text=Chapter 3 .
#Text=XLIII .
#Text=My father took a single turn across the room , then sat down , and finished the chapter .

#Text=The verbs auxiliary we are concerned in here , continued my father , are , am ; was ; have ; had ; do ; did ; make ; made ; suffer ; shall ; should ; will ; would ; can ; could ; owe ; ought ; used ; or is wont . --
#Text=And these varied with tenses , present , past , future , and conjugated with the verb see , -- or with these questions added to them ; -- Is it ?
#Text=Was it ?
#Text=Will it be ?
#Text=Would it be ?
#Text=May it be ?
#Text=Might it be ?
#Text=And these again put negatively , Is it not ?
#Text=Was it not ?
#Text=Ought it not ?
#Text=-- Or affirmatively , -- It is ; It was ; It ought to be .
#Text=Or chronologically , -- Has it been always ?
#Text=Lately ?
#Text=How long ago ?
#Text=-- Or hypothetically , -- If it was ?
#Text=If it was not ?
#Text=What would follow ?
#Text=-- If the French should beat the English ?
#Text=If the Sun go out of the Zodiac ?

#Text=Now , by the right use and application of these , continued my father , in which a child 's memory should be exercised , there is no one idea can enter his brain , how barren soever , but a magazine of conceptions and conclusions may be drawn forth from it .
#Text=-- Didst thou ever see a white bear ? cried my father , turning his head round to Trim , who stood at the back of his chair : --
#Text=No , an ' please your honour , replied the corporal .
#Text=-- But thou couldst discourse about one , Trim , said my father , in case of need ? --
#Text=How is it possible , brother , quoth my uncle Toby , if the corporal never saw one ? -- 'Tis the fact I want , replied my father , -- and the possibility of it is as follows .
